Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @Echalion shallot{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and rinse the @cannellini beans{1}(drained and rinsed) in a #sieve{}. Cut the @baking potato{1}(cut into 2cm chunks) in 2cm chunks and put on a #baking tray{} with a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle}, @salt{some} and @pepper{some}. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}, turning half way through cooking.

Once the potatoes have been in the oven for ~{5%minutes}, add the @Toulouse sausages{4} to the same #tray{} and return to the oven for the remaining ~{20-25%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The sausages are cooked when they are no longer pink in the middle.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on a medium high heat. Once hot add the @Panko breadcrumbs{10} and half the garlic, cook until the crumbs are golden brown, stirring frequently, ~{2-4%minutes}.

> TIP: Watch them like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Pour into a #bowl{} and set aside.

Return the frying pan to the medium high heat and add a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle}. When hot add the shallot and cook until soft, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the remaining garlic and cook for a further ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @water{300%ml}, @red wine jus paste{1} and @tomato puree{30} to the pan with the shallot. Mix well and add the @chopped Cavolo Nero{100%g}(chopped) and cannellini beans. Bring to a boil and then reduce the heat down to a simmer. Cover with a #lid{} or #tin foil{} and cook until the cavolo nero is tender, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it.

> TIP: Add a splash of water too if the liquid has boiled off too much.

Serve the bean stew between your #bowls{} and top with the roasted potatoes. Pop sausages on top and sprinkle over the crumb. Enjoy!